meta.meta: Pterosphenoid. -- A thin plate; cartilage filled along its dorsal edge:
Pterotic: only moderately prolonged posteriorly as a stout bone, about as long as wide

Exoccipital. —Cartilage filled at its anterior and ventromedial edges; articulates by interdigitation ventromedially with the basioccipital, posterolaterally with the pterotic, anterodorsally with the epiotic, and antero- ventrally with the prootic.:
Supracleithrum: not very elongate, only its extreme proximate end articulated directly with the pterotic
Supraoccipital crest: long, thin, projecting backward
Interopercle: with a ventral flange and posterior shaft-like portion extending at least a short distance posteriorly beyond the level of the epihyal
Caudal fin: relatively normal, with 9 to 12 rays supported by variously consolidated and fused but normal vertebral elements
Dorsal-, anal-, caudal-, and pectoral-fin rays: most fin rays less extensively branched but with a normal amount of cross-striations, these not confined to only the distal end of the rays
Supraoccipital. —A rounded plate anteriorly, but drawn out posteriorly into a long, laterally compressed spine;:
Supraoccipital crest: long, thin, projecting backward
Coracoid: short and wide, with a posterodorsal prong below the lower actinost always developed to some degree
Caudal fin: relatively normal, with 9 to 12 rays supported by variously consolidated and fused but normal vertebral elements
Dorsal-, anal-, caudal-, and pectoral-fin rays: most fin rays less extensively branched but with a normal amount of cross-striations, these not confined to only the distal end of the rays
Symplectic: small, extending posteriorly only about one-half the length of the metapterygoid
First basal pterygiophore of dorsal fin: not in contact or only slightly in contact with the second pterygiophore
Most of basal pterygiophores of dorsal and anal fins: long slender rods
Dorsal- and anal-fin rays: not widely separated from their basal pterygial supports by a large block of cartilage
Dorsal-, anal-, caudal-, and pectoral-fin rays: most fin rays less extensively branched but with a normal amount of cross-striations, these not confined to only the distal end of the rays
Posteriormost pterygiophores of dorsal and anal fins: inserted highly oblique to body axis (45° or less)
Mesopterygoid: in contact with the metapterygoid
Symplectic: small, extending posteriorly only about one-half the length of the metapterygoid
Mesopterygoid: large element, sometimes elongate, at least one-half the size of the ectopterygoid
Premaxillae: articulated to one another by interdigitation or by regular interlocking emarginations
Teeth in biting edge of beak: retaining much of their individual identity

Exoccipitals: with condyles and in contact with the first vertebra, which articulates anteriorly with both the exoccipitals and the basioccipital, and the latter not prolonged dorsally behind the exoccipitals, the exoccipitals bordering all but the bottom edge of the foramen magnum

Exoccipital. —Cartilage filled at its anterior and ventromedial edges; articulates by interdigitation ventromedially with the basioccipital, posterolaterally with the pterotic, anterodorsally with the epiotic, and antero- ventrally with the prootic.:

Hyomandibular. —Expanded dorsally, tapering to a stout shaft anteroventrally;:
Parasphenoid. —Elongate, with a well-developed ventral keel in the suborbital region.:
